 <section id="gan-technology" class="mb-16">
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">1. GaN Technology: What Is It?</h2>
<p>GaN stands for Gallium Nitride, a semiconductor material that has triggered a revolution in charger technology in recent years. Unlike traditional silicon, GaN has a significantly wider bandgap (3.4 eV vs. 1.1 eV), which brings multiple advantages: higher switching frequencies, lower conduction losses, and better thermal conductivity. The result is chargers that are half the size of their silicon counterparts at the same power level, run significantly cooler, and waste less energy.</p>
<p>GaN technology is not new — it has been used for decades in LED lighting and RF amplifiers. But only in recent years has the industry learned to produce GaN components cost-effectively for consumer chargers and power adapters. Today, GaN chargers are no longer a niche technology but a fast-growing mainstream market with over 200 million units sold annually. Analysts forecast the GaN power semiconductor market to grow at over 30% CAGR through 2030, reaching approximately $12 billion. In the charger segment, GaN-based products are projected to capture over 40% of the total market by 2028.</p>
<p>The breakthrough came when manufacturers like Navitas, GaN Systems, and Innoscience began offering GaN transistors in standard packages compatible with conventional manufacturing processes. This allowed charger OEMs to switch to GaN without expensive retooling. GaN components switch at frequencies up to ten times higher than silicon, enabling smaller transformers, more compact heatsinks, and dramatically smaller charger form factors overall.</p>

