 <section id="gan-advantages" class="mb-16">
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">3. Advantages of GaN Chargers</h2>

<h3>1. Significantly Smaller Form Factor</h3>
<p>The most obvious advantage of GaN chargers is their size. A modern 65W GaN charger is no larger than a traditional 20W silicon adapter from years past, yet delivers over three times the power at half the weight. A 100W GaN charger fits comfortably in the palm of your hand, while a comparable silicon adapter would be three to four times larger. For travelers and power users, this is a decisive advantage. In retail — both online and brick-and-mortar — compact GaN chargers win on shelf presence and premium perception.</p>

<h3>2. Higher Energy Efficiency</h3>
<p>GaN chargers convert more than 95% of input energy into usable charging power. Traditional silicon adapters typically achieve only 85-90% efficiency. The difference may seem small, but over daily use across multiple devices it compounds — saving several kilowatt-hours annually. Less energy loss also means less heat generation. GaN chargers remain comfortably cool even under sustained full load, extending component lifespan and reducing failure rates.</p>

<h3>3. Lower Heat Generation</h3>
<p>Heat is the #1 enemy and most common failure cause for electronic components. GaN components are inherently more efficient and generate significantly less waste heat than comparable silicon components. Additionally, GaN chargers can operate at higher ambient temperatures without performance throttling (no thermal throttling). This is particularly advantageous in warmer climates, under heavy use, or in continuous operation. For manufacturers, lower heat means reduced heatsink and enclosure requirements — saving additional cost and space.</p>

<h3>4. Higher Power Density</h3>
<p>GaN enables multi-port chargers with high total power in a compact enclosure. A modern 4-port GaN charger with 100W total output and PD 3.1 support is now no larger than an older 2-port silicon adapter at 30W. This makes GaN the ideal technology for modern multi-device chargers and power strips, where users want to simultaneously charge a laptop, smartphone, tablet, and headphones.</p>

